# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pony-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:pony-language/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:pony-language/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:pony-language/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:pony-language/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A capability-based system, in contrast, is designed with that goal in mind.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Capabilities achieve their objective of improving system security by being used in place of forgeable references.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A forgeable reference (for example, a path name) identifies an object, but does not specify which access rights are appropriate for that object and the user program which holds that reference.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Consequently, any attempt to access the referenced object must be validated by the operating system, based on the ambient authority of the requesting program, typically via the use of an access-control list (ACL).
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Instead, in a system with capabilities, the mere fact that a user program possesses that capability entitles it to use the referenced object in accordance with the rights that are specified by that capability.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In theory, a system with capabilities removes the need for any access control list or similar mechanism by giving all entities all and only the capabilities they will actually need.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A capability is typically implemented as a privileged data structure that consists of a section that specifies access rights, and a section that uniquely identifies the object to be accessed.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The user does not access the data structure or object directly, but instead via a handle.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In practice, it is used much like a file descriptor in a traditional operating system (a traditional handle), but to access every object on the system.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Capabilities are typically stored by the operating system in a list, with some mechanism in place to prevent the program from directly modifying the contents of the capability (so as to forge access rights or change the object it points to).
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Some systems have also been based on capability-based addressing (hardware support for capabilities), such as Plessey System 250.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Programs possessing capabilities can perform functions on them, such as passing them on to other programs, converting them to a less-privileged version, or deleting them.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The operating system must ensure that only specific operations can occur to the capabilities in the system, in order to maintain the integrity of the security policy.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Capabilities as discussed in this article should not be confused with Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) 1e/2c "Capabilities".
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The latter are coarse-grained privileges that cannot be transferred between processes.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A capability is defined to be a protected object reference which, by virtue of its possession by a user process, grants that process the capability (hence the name) to interact with an object in certain ways.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Those ways might include reading data associated with an object, modifying the object, executing the data in the object as a process, and other conceivable access rights.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The capability logically consists of a reference that uniquely identifies a particular object and a set of one or more of these rights.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Although this identifies a unique object on the system, it does not specify access rights and hence is not a capability.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] This pair identifies an object along with a set of access rights.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The pair, however, is still not a capability because the user process's *possession* of these values says nothing about whether that access would actually be legitimate.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The variable `fd` now contains the index of a file descriptor in the process's file descriptor table.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Its existence in the process's file descriptor table is sufficient to show that the process does indeed have legitimate access to the object.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A key feature of this arrangement is that the file descriptor table is in kernel memory and cannot be directly manipulated by the user program.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In traditional operating systems, programs often communicate with each other and with storage using references like those in the first two examples.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Path names are often passed as command-line parameters, sent via sockets, and stored on disk.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] These references are not capabilities, and must be validated before they can be used.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In these systems, a central question is "on whose *authority* is a given reference to be evaluated?" This becomes a critical issue especially for processes which must act on behalf of two different authority-bearing entities.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] They become susceptible to a programming error known as the confused deputy problem, very frequently resulting in a security hole.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In a capability-based system, the capabilities themselves are passed between processes and storage using a mechanism that is known by the operating system to maintain the integrity of those capabilities.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] One novel approach to solving this problem involves the use of an orthogonally persistent operating system.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In such a system, there is no need for entities to be discarded and their capabilities be invalidated, and hence require an ACL-like mechanism to restore those capabilities at a later time.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] The operating system maintains the integrity and security of the capabilities contained within all storage, both volatile and nonvolatile, at all times; in part by performing all serialization tasks by itself, rather than requiring user programs to do so, as is the case in most operating systems.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Because user programs are relieved of this responsibility, there is no need to trust them to reproduce only legal capabilities, nor to validate requests for access using an access control mechanism.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] An example implementation is the Flex machine from the early 1980s.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) draft 1003.1e specifies a concept of permissions called "capabilities".
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] However, POSIX capabilities differ from capabilities in this article.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] A POSIX capability is not associated with any object; a process having CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability can listen on any TCP port under 1024.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In contrast, Capsicum Unix hybridizes a true capability-system model with a Unix design and POSIX API.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] Capsicum capabilities are a refined form of file descriptor, a delegable right between processes and additional object types beyond classic POSIX, such as processes, can be referenced via capabilities.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] In Capsicum capability mode, processes are unable to utilize global namespaces (such as the filesystem namespace) to look up objects, and must instead inherit or be delegated them.
[src:pony-language/capability-based-security] This system is found natively in FreeBSD, but patches are available to other systems.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:pony-language/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Memory errors were first considered in the context of resource management (computing) and time-sharing systems, in an effort to avoid problems such as fork bombs.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Developments were mostly theoretical until the Morris worm, which exploited a buffer overflow in fingerd.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] The field of computer security developed quickly thereafter, escalating with multitudes of new attacks such as the return-to-libc attack and defense techniques such as the non-executable stack and address space layout randomization.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Randomization prevents most buffer overflow attacks and requires the attacker to use heap spraying or other application-dependent methods to obtain addresses, although its adoption has been slow.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] However, deployments of the technology are typically limited to randomizing libraries and the location of the stack.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] In 2019, a Microsoft security engineer reported that 70% of all security vulnerabilities were caused by memory safety issues.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] In 2020, a team at Google similarly reported that 70% of all "severe security bugs" in Chromium were caused by memory safety problems.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Many other high-profile vulnerabilities and exploits in critical software have ultimately stemmed from a lack of memory safety, including Heartbleed and a long-standing privilege escalation bug in sudo.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] The pervasiveness and severity of vulnerabilities and exploits arising from memory safety issues have led several security researchers to describe identifying memory safety issues as "shooting fish in a barrel".
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Some modern high-level programming languages are memory-safe by default, though not completely since they only check their own code and not the system they interact with.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Automatic memory management in the form of garbage collection is the most common technique for preventing some of the memory safety problems, since it prevents common memory safety errors like use-after-free for all data allocated within the language runtime.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] However, the performance overhead of garbage collection makes these languages unsuitable for certain performance-critical applications.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] For languages that use manual memory management, memory safety is not usually guaranteed by the runtime.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Instead, memory safety properties must either be guaranteed by the compiler via static program analysis and automated theorem proving or carefully managed by the programmer at runtime.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] For example, the Rust programming language implements a borrow checker to ensure memory safety, while C and C++ provide no memory safety guarantees.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] The substantial amount of software written in C and C++ has motivated the development of external static analysis tools like Coverity, which offers static memory analysis for C.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] DieHard, its redesign DieHarder, and the Allinea Distributed Debugging Tool are special heap allocators that allocate objects in their own random virtual memory page, allowing invalid reads and writes to be stopped and debugged at the exact instruction that causes them.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Protection relies upon hardware memory protection and thus overhead is typically not substantial, although it can grow significantly if the program makes heavy use of allocation.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Randomization provides only probabilistic protection against memory errors, but can often be easily implemented in existing software by relinking the binary.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] The memcheck tool of Valgrind uses an instruction set simulator and runs the compiled program in a memory-checking virtual machine, providing guaranteed detection of a subset of runtime memory errors.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] However, it typically slows the program down by a factor of 40, and furthermore must be explicitly informed of custom memory allocators.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] With access to the source code, libraries exist that collect and track legitimate values for pointers ("metadata") and check each pointer access against the metadata for validity, such as the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] In general, memory safety can be safely assured using tracing garbage collection and the insertion of runtime checks on every memory access; this approach has overhead, but less than that of Valgrind.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] All garbage-collected languages take this approach.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] For C and C++, many tools exist that perform a compile-time transformation of the code to do memory safety checks at runtime, such as CheckPointer and AddressSanitizer which imposes an average slowdown factor of 2.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] BoundWarden is a new spatial memory enforcement approach that utilizes a combination of compile-time transformation and runtime concurrent monitoring techniques.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Fuzz testing is well-suited for finding memory safety bugs and is often used in combination with dynamic checkers such as AddressSanitizer.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Some lists may also include **race conditions** (concurrent reads/writes to shared memory) as being part of memory safety (e.g., for access control).
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] The Rust programming language prevents many kinds of memory-based race conditions by default, because it ensures there is at most one writer *or* one or more readers.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Many other programming languages, such as Java, do *not* automatically prevent memory-based race conditions, yet are still generally considered "memory safe" languages.
[src:pony-language/memory-safety] Therefore, countering race conditions is generally *not* considered necessary for a language to be considered memory safe.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:pony-language/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] The **object-capability model** is a computer security model.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] A capability describes a transferable right to perform one (or more) operations on a given object.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] The security model relies on not being able to forge references.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Parenthood: If A creates B, at that moment A obtains the only reference to the newly created B.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Endowment: If A creates B, B is born with that subset of A's references with which A chose to endow it.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Introduction: If A has references to both B and C, A can send to B a message containing a reference to C.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] B can retain that reference for subsequent use.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] In the object-capability model, *all* computation is performed following the above rules.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Advantages that motivate object-oriented programming, such as encapsulation or information hiding, modular programming (modularity), and separation of concerns, correspond to security goals such as least privilege and privilege separation in capability-based programming.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] The object-capability model was first proposed by Jack Dennis and Earl C.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Such use of *undeniable authority* violates the conditions of the object-capability model.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Caja and Joe-E are variants of JavaScript and Java, respectively, that impose restrictions to eliminate these loopholes.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Dean Tribble stated that in smart contracts, identity-based access control did not support well dynamically changing permissions, compared to the object-capability model.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] He analogized the ocap model with giving a valet the key to a car, without giving the right to car ownership.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] The structural properties of object capability systems favor modularity in code design and ensure reliable encapsulation in code implementation.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] These structural properties facilitate the analysis of some security properties of an object-capability program or operating system.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Some of these, specifically information flow properties, can be analyzed at the level of object references and connectivity, independent of any knowledge or analysis of the code that determines the behavior of the objects.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] As a consequence, these security properties can be established and maintained in the presence of new objects that contain unknown and possibly malicious code.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] As a consequence of these two rules, an object can obtain a reference to another object only through a preexisting chain of references.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] A computational system that implements principles described in this article.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] in the sense used in the access control literature.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] An unforgeable communications channel (protected pointer, opaque address) that unambiguously designates one object, and provides permission to send messages to that object.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Depending on the system, messages may or may not be first-class objects.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] An operation in which a message is sent on a reference.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] When the message is received, the receiver will have access to any references included in the message.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] in object-capability systems: given one reference of an object, create another reference for a proxy object with certain security restrictions, such as only permitting read-only access or allowing revocation.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] The proxy object performs security checks on messages that it receives and passes on any that are allowed.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] Almost all historical systems that have been described as *capability systems* can be modeled as object-capability systems.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] However, some uses of the term *capability* are inconsistent with the model, such as POSIX *capabilities*.
[src:pony-language/object-capability-model] KeyKOS, EROS, Integrity (operating system), CapROS, Coyotos, seL4, OKL4 and Fiasco.OC are secure operating systems that implement the object-capability model.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] The language was created by Sylvan Clebsch, while a PhD student at Imperial College London.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] His professor at that time was Sophia Drossopoulou, who is also well known for her contributions to computer programming, and as a lecturer.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] According to developers who have talked to Sylvan, he was frustrated with not having a high performance language that could run concurrent code securely, safely, and more simply.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] At its core, Pony is a systems language designed around safety and performance.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] In Pony, instead of a main function, there is a main *actor*.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] The creation of this actor serves as the entry point into a Pony program, as in this "Hello, World!" program.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] There are no global variables in Pony, meaning everything must be contained within an instance of a class or an actor.
[src:pony-language/pony-programming-language] As such, even the environment that allows for printing to standard output is passed as a parameter.
